Our predictions were obtained on coupled SF-RR networks, and it is legitimate to seek for generality of the two peaks pattern phenomenon, by means of investigating coupled networks with other topological structures. For this purpose, we have also studied the case of SF-SF and RR-RR networks, respectively. Very interestingly, one finds that the pattern of two peaks can be still observed by adjusting the coupling strength between the coupled layers (see Fig. 8
). Although the two coupled SF networks (or the two coupled RR networks) can be considered as the case with same heterogeneity, they are produced independently and thus their network topologies are different, indicating that there exists still the effect of heterogeneity between the two coupled networks. On the other hand, extension to three-layered model was also considered, and it was found that there is a small probability to produce a pattern of three peaks (see Fig. 9
). Therefore, while in principle one can expect a multi-peaks pattern to occur in a multilayered network, the majority of unusual cases (i.e. cases in which the epidemic event is not happening with a single maximum of infected density) will be characterized by just two peaks, in full consistency with the data of Fig. 1.
